                        <h4><i class="fa fa-paintbrush fa-fw"></i> Paint Still Image</h4>
                        <p>I then move to painting. I always start by looking at the image on a screen, rather than using the projector to trace shapes or build out the composition.  I find that there is a traced, flat look that occurs if one doesn't use the </p><p>To build up richness, I work with an underpainting and slowly build in detail, only where appropriate to add focus. Often, there are two or three completely different paintings under the final image that help to build up texture.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <hr class="small">
            <div class="row text-left">
                <div class="col-md-2 col-md-offset-2">
                    <img class="img-process img-responsive" src="assets/after-effects-example.png">
                </div>
                <div class="col-md-6">
                        <h4><i class="fa fa-video-camera fa-fw"></i> Re-work Video and Painting Simultaneously</h4>
                        <p>Once the painting is close, I will move to the projector and begin building up the motion portion in after effects.  I have a large collection of original video and found video, and I combine them in as many as 15 to 20 layers to create the finished motion. While doing this, I can preview the projection on the wall, and make changes to the painting as well.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <hr class="small">
            <div class="row text-left">
                <div class="col-md-2 col-md-offset-2">
                    <img class="img-process img-responsive" src="assets/in-gallery.jpg">
                </div>
                <div class="col-md-6">
                        <h4><i class="fa fa-video-camera fa-fw"></i> Install Projection</h4>
                        <p>Installation was on of the primary challenges of this process. There are significant technical barriers to installing a video that can loop indefinitely and can be flexibly positioned on the wall and create the illusion that it's.</p>
                        <p>To accomplish this, I programmed a custom application that allows me to adjust size, position, perspective, and rotation for a video, and then seamlessly loops. This allows the work to be on display, uninterrupted, for a month long show</p>
                </div>
            </div>
